<BaseLayout title="About — Hyungwoo Song" lang="en"><section class="page-hero about-hero"><div class="wrap"><div class="eyebrow">About</div><h1 class="page-title">I study technologies that help people live more human lives.</h1><p class="lead">As AI takes on more tasks, I care about how people can keep judgment, voice, relationships, and dignity.</p></div></section><section class="section"><div class="wrap about-grid"><img class="about-photo" src={profile.portrait} alt="Portrait of Hyungwoo Song"><div class="about-copy"><p>Hyungwoo Song is a Ph.D. student in Intelligence and Information at Seoul National University. His research sits at the intersection of HCI, human-centered AI, accessibility, education, and healthcare.</p><p>He is less interested in automation as an end in itself, and more interested in what people gain or lose when AI begins to speak, suggest, summarize, judge, and act. His work asks who gets to speak, whose experience is preserved, and what kinds of support scaffold people rather than replace them.</p><p>This connects projects that may look different on the surface: accessibility and alt text, communication between students with disabilities and peer note-takers, healthcare adaptation for North Korean defectors, AI shopping agents, information access, and AI-supported learning. The shared question is how technology can make life more humane, not merely more efficient.</p><div class="about-links"><a class="btn" href="/research/">Research</a><a class="btn secondary" href="/publications/">Publications</a><a class="btn secondary" href={profile.cv}>CV</a></div></div></div></section></BaseLayout>